@stevecollins4567 it is easier to understand if you just look at an image of a Halbach array. Do an image search on Google for "Halbach array" and you'll quickly understand.

Between the alternating north-south magnets there are magnets whose axes are oriented sideways, perpendicular to the main magnets. These force all of the magnetic field to one side of the array, roughly doubling its strength on one side and roughly canceling all of it out on the other.

This basically doubles the efficiency with which your magnetic field is being used because as much of it as possible is being forced to sweep through the coil. Without the Halbach array, half of the magnetic field (the half facing away from the coil) never passes through the coil at all.
